sf_uiModel.markdownText:
`CPU  Shares % used` shows the actual percent of shares used by a container. By default containers receive equal shares. However, if certain containers do not use CPU, other containers in need can use more (if quota is not exceeded). Consistently having greater than a 100 percent of CPU shares, suggests that a container is under provisioned. `CPU  Quota % used` is the percent of CPU time used by containers as a limit of the quota set (if any). Using this chart in combination with `Throttled Periods % by container` and `Throttled Time by container` would provide explanation for lag in application because once a container uses up its quota in a period, it gets throttled and has to wait for the next period to get scheduled. These charts can be used to identify both containers that are under and over provisioned, depending on how much cpu quota is used.

Note - Shares indicate a relative measure of priority. Whereas, Quota is an absolute limit enforced on containers.

`Memory % by Container` gives the amount memory used by a container w.r.t its allocated limit. Containers can use more memory if swap memory is set accordingly. The overhead is that swap memory usage is slow and should be avoided if possible. Looking at the above chart in conjunction with `Swap Memory by Container` will give an idea of memory usage of containers and whether the allocations are reasonable. Using [swap memory](https://docs.docker.com/engine/admin/resource_constraints/#--memory-swap-details) by Docker.
